# üêû bug report

> Note: This bug report is specifically for IE11.


### Affected Package
I believe it would be @angular/core? It would be whatever handles transpiling for ES5. I am using 8.2.14 at the moment.


### Is this a regression?
I don't know as this is the first version I have used.

### Description
If I use the object notation on an element using [ngClass] like so:

`<ul [ngClass]="{'hidden': activeLoc}">`

`activeLoc` is a number in my case. In some cases it is undefined.

IE 11 reports a very vague error saying `Object expected` and after I dug around in the stack trace it pointed to this function in vendor-es5.js on line 82596 (I know that line number will be different for other folk). This error causes the rest of the application not to work by the way.

```
    function iterateListLike$1(obj, fn) {
      if (Array.isArray(obj)) {
        for (var i = 0; i < obj.length; i++) {
          fn(obj[i]);
        }
      } else {
        /** @type {?} */
        var iterator = obj[getSymbolIterator()]();
        /** @type {?} */

        var item;

        while (!(item = iterator.next()).done) {
          fn(item.value);
        }
      }
    }
```
I ended up adding a console log in this vendor file to see what `obj` was and the stack trace in IE11 was an object with a 'hidden': undefined property in it. The fix for me was to use a ternary function. After I did this and rebuilt, the error went away in IE 11.

`<ul [ngClass]="(activeLoc) ? 'hidden' : ''">`


